      <pubDate>Thu, 20 Oct 2022 21:00:00 -0700</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://boat.karlnelson.net/posts/10-all-the-boats-i-didnt-build/</guid>
      <description>As I mentioned earlier, when searching for the right boat to build, I&amp;rsquo;d compiled a list of about 30 different plans. I thought it might be fun to look at some of the boats I&amp;rsquo;m not going to build.
Perhaps it is my Scandinavian heritage, but I love a double-ender. Sjogin is a great example of a small and beamy double-ender, but at just over 20 feet, it is quite a bit larger than what I&amp;rsquo;d want to tackle as a first project.</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Spar Gauge</title>
      <link>https://boat.karlnelson.net/posts/9-spar-gauge/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 16 Oct 2022 17:00:00 -0700</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://boat.karlnelson.net/posts/9-spar-gauge/</guid>
      <description>To go from a square-sectioned spar to a round spar, one first needs to go from four sides to eight sides, and then to 16 sides. To make it easier to create eight equal sides, pretty much every tutorial on the subject recommends a spar gauge.
A spar gauge is necessary because of the spars taper. In the case of the first spar I&amp;rsquo;m making, the gaff, it goes from 58mm at the thickest to 36mm on one end and 50mm on the other.</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Handplanes</title>
      <link>https://boat.karlnelson.net/posts/8-handplanes/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 02 Oct 2022 17:00:00 -0700</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://boat.karlnelson.net/posts/8-handplanes/</guid>
      <description>For now, at least, I&amp;rsquo;m using hand planes to shape the spars. Pretty much every how-to video you&amp;rsquo;ll see on spars shows the use of a power plane (perhaps after a band saw has roughed out the shape.) Well, I don&amp;rsquo;t have a power plane (although one could be had at the tool library), but I also rather like the notion of shaping these pieces by hand.
Hand planes are quiet.</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Starting the Boom and Gaff</title>
      <link>https://boat.karlnelson.net/posts/7-boom-and-gaff/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 25 Sep 2022 16:30:00 -0700</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://boat.karlnelson.net/posts/7-boom-and-gaff/</guid>
      <description>With the help of my neighbor (and tool library shop steward) Joel, I hauled a couple of ~14 foot Sitka spruce boards to the tool library with the intention of turning them into smaller pieces of Sitka spruce that could then be glued up into blanks for the boom and the gaff. (The gaff, for those who don&amp;rsquo;t know the term, is the spar at the top of the sail in a gaff rigged boat.</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Bowsprit</title>
      <link>https://boat.karlnelson.net/posts/6-bowsprit/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 24 Sep 2022 19:52:00 -0700</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://boat.karlnelson.net/posts/6-bowsprit/</guid>
      <description>I decided to start with the bowsprit (aka the pointy bit at the front of the boat). It is the shortest of the spars, although, except for the mast, perhaps the most complicated. And, since I have to start somewhere, why not start at the front?
I started by turning one of the spruce boards into three spruce boards.
This was done at the table saw at my local tool library.</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Thinking about spars</title>
      <link>https://boat.karlnelson.net/posts/5-thinking-about-spars/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 26 Jun 2022 19:52:00 -0700</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://boat.karlnelson.net/posts/5-thinking-about-spars/</guid>
      <description>I&amp;rsquo;m going to start by making the spars – the mast, gaff, boom, and bowsprit.
There are a couple of reasons for this:
Once the hull is done, it&amp;rsquo;ll provide me with a faster path to the water if I don&amp;rsquo;t then have to make the spars. More importantly, they take up less space in the garage, meaning the garage doesn&amp;rsquo;t have to be completely cleared out in order for me to start.</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Yak Shaving</title>
      <link>https://boat.karlnelson.net/posts/4-yak-shaving/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 20 Feb 2022 09:00:00 -0700</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://boat.karlnelson.net/posts/4-yak-shaving/</guid>
      <description>&amp;ldquo;Yak Shaving&amp;rdquo; is a term that comes out of the technology space (where I spend my days). It is best defined as:
yak shaving is what you are doing when you&amp;rsquo;re doing some stupid, fiddly little task that bears no obvious relationship to what you&amp;rsquo;re supposed to be working on, but yet a chain of twelve causal relations links what you&amp;rsquo;re doing to the original meta-task.
In the software world, it isn&amp;rsquo;t uncommon to be working on adding a feature, then realize that that feature needs a updated version of some software library.</description>
    </item>
    
